    "ocr_text": "Mr. W. D. Wells,
321 East 18th Avenue,
Denver, Colorado.

Dear Sir and Brother:
Your favor of the 18th instant to hand and contents noted.
In view of the fact of your leaving Nevada and traveling through
several parts of the country I shall have no hesitancy in issuing
a commission to you as organizer for the United States, but there
is a matter in your letter which makes it necessary to be exceedingly
careful in regard thereto. You say that you are in the
advertising business. I want you to believe that I do not wish in
any way to reflect upon you or your course or the use to which you
would put the commission, but we have had so much to contend with
in matters of this kind that it would be necessary for me to have
some additional information before I can comply with your request.
We have had men who have had commissions, men who have been really
good and true, but who later have launched out in the advertising
business and the organizer's commission they have held were used
by them both directly and indirectly as a means to launch several
publications, such as souvenirs, directories, and so-called histories
and bulletins and though they have organized a union here and there
yet they left each town in such a condition as to bring an uneasy
regards to the labor organizations of these places. As I say, I do
